ood; professionalism, vocation and domesticity; race, gender and generation, this first in-depth study of missionary families reveals their profound importance to the missionary enterprise, and concludes that mission history can no longer be written without attention to the personal, emotional and intimate aspects of missionary lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMissionariesxFamily relationshipsxHistoryy19th century. 0aMissionaries' spousesy19th century. 0aMissionsxHistoryy19th century. 0aMissionszEnglandzLondonxHistoryy19th century. 0aMissionszFrench PolynesiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aMissionszSouth AfricaxHistoryy19th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aLondon Missionary Society.  aSouth Africa Mission.  aSouth Seas Mission.  acompanionate marriage.  agendered roles.  amissionary children.  amissionary families.  amissionary fathers.  amissionary marriage.  amissionary mothers.  amissionary wife.  aracial intermarriage.  asecond-generation missionaries.  aspiritual frontier.1 aManktelow, Emily J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611153140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526111531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526111531/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles